no identities (in the American sense) to steal. However, as Miller demonstrates, this too is a ruse: French universalism can only go so far and do so much. There is plenty of otherness to appropriate. This French and Francophone tradition of imposture has never received the study it deserves. Taking a novel approach to this understudied tradition, Impostors examines hoaxes in both countries, finding similar practices of deception and questions of harm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican literature (French)xHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aHoaxes. 0aLiterary forgeries and mystifications. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCamara Laye.  aJack-Alain Léger.  aRomain Gary.  aauthenticity.  acultural appropriation.  aharm.  ahoax.  aimposture.  aplay.  atruth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226591148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226591148/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles